## Phase 5 — Boundary Rules

**About ↔ Orchestrators**: _Protocol economics vs operator economics_
Rule: About owns why the incentive system exists and how it works at the protocol level. Orchestrators owns what specific numbers an operator should target, how to configure them, and what thresholds matter operationally. The line is drawn at: "does this help someone understand the system?" (About) vs "does this help someone run a node?" (Orchestrators).

**About ↔ LP Token**: _Token concept vs token mechanics_
Rule: About owns LPT as a protocol-securing mechanism — why it exists, its relationship to inflation and staking security. LP Token owns every action: acquiring LPT, delegating, reading reward/fee cut, voting on LIPs. The line is drawn at: can the reader take an action from this content? If yes, it belongs in LP Token.

**About ↔ Community**: _Protocol governance vs community participation_
Rule: About owns governance as a protocol feature — LIPs, upgrade process, how changes are ratified. Community owns the human layer — how to engage in governance discourse, workstreams, and participation culture. The line is drawn at: is this about the protocol mechanism, or about how people organise around it?

**Solutions ↔ Developers**: _Evaluation vs integration_
Rule: Solutions owns the business case — what Livepeer does, why it is the right choice, what you get. Developers owns the technical path — how to integrate, call APIs, build pipelines. The line is drawn at: does the reader need to have already decided to use Livepeer? If yes, it is Developers. If they are still deciding, it is Solutions.

**Gateways ↔ Developers**: _Running infra vs consuming infra_
Rule: Developers owns all SDK-based and API-based access to Livepeer compute, including custom gateway SDKs used programmatically. Gateways owns `go-livepeer` node operation — installation, configuration, on-chain setup, routing economics. The line is drawn at: is the reader running a node binary, or writing code that calls a gateway? Binary operation → Gateways. Code → Developers.

**Gateways ↔ Orchestrators**: _Demand side vs supply side_
Rule: Gateways routes compute jobs from clients to orchestrators — demand-side infrastructure. Orchestrators provides GPU compute to fulfil those jobs — supply-side infrastructure. The line is drawn at data flow direction: Gateways owns everything upstream of the job (client → gateway → routing). Orchestrators owns everything downstream (routing → transcoding/inference → result delivery). Shared binary aspects (go-livepeer) are each documented in-tab for that role only; the other tab links rather than duplicates.

**LP Token ↔ Community**: _Voting mechanics vs governance participation_
Rule: LP Token owns the complete voting action — accessing Snapshot, reading proposals, casting votes, tracking outcomes. Community owns the participation culture — where governance discussion happens, how to follow workstreams, how community members shape proposals before they reach a vote. The line is drawn at: is this the action of voting (LP Token) or the culture and context around it (Community)?

**Resource HUB ↔ all role tabs**: _Reference aggregation vs role-specific reference_
Rule: Resource HUB owns any reference item cited by more than one tab — contract addresses, network parameters, glossary terms, audit links, brand assets. Role tabs own reference material that is only ever consulted by their primary audience in the context of that role's operation. A piece of content that is useful to three different audiences belongs in Resource HUB with links from the role tabs — not duplicated across them. The line is drawn at: is this reference material used by one role, or many? Many → Resource HUB.

**Home ↔ all tabs**: _Routing vs content_
Rule: Home owns nothing except the first-impression orientation layer and navigation routing. No content that explains how anything works, how to do anything, or what anything costs belongs on Home. Any content that would be useful on a second visit belongs in a tab, not on Home.

